            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:LeftOperand</td>
                <td>dpv:Impact</td>
                <td>rdf:type</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section id="sector"> 
    <h3>Sector</h3>

    <p>
        DPV's sector concepts can be used to permit or prohibit the usage of certain assets depending on the area of application or domain that they are to be used. For this purpose, the [[[EU-AIAct]]] extension provides concepts to represent, e.g., the education or the employment sector.
    </p>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>External Concept</th>
                <th>DPV Concept</th>
                <th>Mapping Type</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:LeftOperand</td>
                <td>dpv:Sector</td>
                <td>rdf:type</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section id="status">
    <h3>Status</h3>

    <p>
        DPV's status concepts can be used to indicate information regarding the status or state of a certain process or activity. For instance, it can be used to permit the usage of a certain asset only if the consent status for that usage is valid, i.e., using the <code>dpv:ConsentStatusValidForProcessing</code> concept.
    </p>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>External Concept</th>
                <th>DPV Concept</th>
                <th>Mapping Type</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:LeftOperand</td>
                <td>dpv:Status</td>
                <td>rdf:type</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

  </section>

  <section id="rules"> 
    <h3>Rules</h3>

    <p>
        DPV's sector concepts can be used to permit or prohibit the usage of certain assets depending on the area of application or domain that they are to be used. For this purpose, the [[[EU-AIAct]]] extension provides concepts to represent, e.g., the education or the employment sector.
    </p>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>External Concept</th>
                <th>DPV Concept</th>
                <th>Mapping Type</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:Permission</td>
                <td>dpv:Permission</td>
                <td>skos:related</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:Prohibition</td>
                <td>dpv:Prohibition</td>
                <td>skos:related</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>odrl:Duty</td>
                <td>dpv:Obligation</td>
                <td>skos:related</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <aside class="note" title="dpv:Recommendation and dpv:Deterrence rules can be considered for ODRL 3.0">
        <p>
            <code>dpv:Recommendation</code> and <code>dpv:Deterrence</code> rules are modelled in DPV, with no equivalent concepts being present in ODRL. These rules can be considered for ODRL 3.0 or can be modelled as ODRL rules in this profile extension.
        </p>
    </aside>

    <aside class="note" title="dpv:RuleFulfilmentStatus to be aligned with ODRL formal semantics work">
        <p>
            DPV's <code>RuleFulfilmentStatus</code> concepts include terms to represent whether a prohibition has been violated or an obligation has been fulfilled. A similar initiative is undergoing in the ODRL CG based on the 
            <a href="https://w3id.org/force/compliance-report">ODRL Compliance Report Model</a>, which is a model and vocabulary that can be used to elaborate the result of an evaluation of ODRL Policy, according to the <a href="https://w3c.github.io/odrl/formal-semantics/">formal semantics of ODRL specification</a>. Once this specification is finalised, DPV's and ODRL's concepts should be aligned for this particular case as well.
        </p>
    </aside>

  </section>

  <section id="policies"> 
    <h3>Contractual Terms and Legal Agreements</h3>

    <p>
        DPV's contractual clauses and legal agreement concepts can be mapped as additional types of ODRL policies.
    </p>

    <aside class="note" title="DPV's terms for contractual clauses and legal agreements can be modelled as types of ODRL policies">
        <p>
            While the mapping below can be used to instantiate DPV concepts such as <code>DataHandlingClause</code> or <code>dpv:NDA</code> as a <code>odrl:Policy</code>, their semantics and practical implementation should be carefully discussed, particularly in terms of mandatory/optional rules, assets, and party roles, as well as the constraints that need to be supported. The DPVCG welcomes contributions for this line of work.
        </p>
    </aside>

    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>External Concept</th>
